04237nam a22005295i 9780774852234DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20071999xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748522347 a10.59962/97807748522342doi  a(DE-B1597)661727  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1089.5.V22bN495 1999eb 7aHIS0030002bisacsh04a305.895/10711331 aNg, Wing Chung, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Chinese in Vancouver, 1945-80 :bThe Pursuit of Identity and Power /cWing Chung Ng. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b12 b&w photos, 17 tables, 4 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContemporary Chinese Studies00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tMaps, Figures, and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Chinese Terms -- tIntroduction -- tEarly Settlement and the Contours of Identity -- tRenewed Immigration and Cultural Redefinition -- tLocal-Born Chinese and the Challenge to an Immigrant Discourse -- tOld-Timers, Public Rituals, and the Resilience of Traditional Organizations -- tNegotiating Identities between Two Worlds, 1945–70 -- tConstructing Chineseness in the Multicultural Arena, 1971–80 -- tBeyond a Conclusion -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn The Chinese in Vancouver, Wing Chung Ng captures the fascinating story of the city's Chinese in their search for identity. He juxtaposes the cultural positions of different generations of Chinese immigrants and their Canadian-born descendants and unveils the ongoing struggle over the definition of being Chinese. It is an engrossing story about cultural identity in the context of migration and settlement, where the influence of the native land and the appeal of the host city continued to impinge on the consciousness of the ethnic Chinese. The Chinese in Canada is long overdue in view of the many previous studies that tend to describe Chinese people as victims of racial prejudice and discrimination and Chinese identity a matter of Western cultural hegemony. Ng's account gives the Chinese people their own voice and shows that the Chinese in Vancouver had much to say and often disagreed about the meaning of being Chinese. In his concluding chapter, Ng looks beyond the Canadian context by engaging in a comparative discussion of the experiences of ethnic Chinese elsewhere in the diaspora. References to the Chinese in various Southeast Asian countries and the U.S. force a rethinking of "Chineseness." He ends with reflections about Vancouver's Chinese community since 1980.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311141940440uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485223440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774852234423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774852234/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141940-4  University of British Columbia eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles